Certainly! Below is an example of a TikZ LaTeX code that generates a graph representing a stochastic compartmental model with three compartments: \( c_0 \), \( c_1 \), and \( c_2 \). The edge from \( c_2 \) to \( c_0 \) has a probability vector with \( 0.3 \) indexed by \( c_1 \) and all other values set to zero.

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm, auto]

    % Define nodes
    \node (c0) [circle, draw] {\( c_0 \)};
    \node (c1) [circle, draw, right of=c0] {\( c_1 \)};
    \node (c2) [circle, draw, right of=c1] {\( c_2 \)};

    % Draw edges with labels
    \draw[-stealth] (c2) -- node[above] {$\left[\begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 0.3 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]$} (c0);
    \draw[-stealth] (c0) -- node[below] {$p_{01}$} (c1);
    \draw[-stealth] (c1) -- node[above] {$p_{12}$} (c2);

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**: Three circular nodes labeled \( c_0 \), \( c_1 \), and \( c_2 \) are created.
- **Edges**:
  - An arrow from \( c_2 \) to \( c_0 \) with a label indicating the probability vector \(\left[\begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 0.3 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]\).
  - Arrows between \( c_0 \) and \( c_1 \) and between \( c_1 \) and \( c_2 \) with generic probabilities \( p_{01} \) and \( p_{12} \).

